<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18290409-321">
               <interp inst="t18290409-321" type="collection" value="BAILEY"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18290409-321" type="year" value="1829"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18290409-321" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18290409"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18290409-321" type="date" value="18290409"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18290409-321-off1809-c2228" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-321-defend2962 t18290409-321-off1809 t18290409-321-verdict1813"></join>
         
               <p>Second London Jury - Before Mr. Common Sergeant.</p>
               <p>998. 
               
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-defend2962" type="defendantName">
                     RICHARD HARPER 
                     GREEN
                  <interp inst="t18290409-321-defend2962" type="surname" value="GREEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-defend2962" type="given" value="RICHARD HARPER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-defend2962" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-defend2962" type="age" value="47"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for that he, on the 17th of July, at St. Botolph Without, Aldersgate, had in his custody and possession a certain bill of exchange, which is as follows, that is to say:</p>
               <p>£23: 14 Dudley, July 23,1828.</p>
               <p>Two months after date, pay to my order, Twenty-three Pounds, Fourteen, Shillings, value received, for 
               <persName id="t18290409-321-person2963">
                  RICHARD 
                  FINCH
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2963" type="surname" value="FINCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2963" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2963" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . To Mr. James Lane, No. 4, Bull Head-court, King-street, Snow-hill, London.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290409-321-off1809" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-off1809" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-off1809" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp>
               on which said bill of exchange was then and there contained a certain false, forged, and counterfeited acceptance of the said bill of exchange, and which said false, forged, and counterfeited acceptance is as follows, "Accepted, 
                     <persName id="t18290409-321-person2964">
                        James 
                        Lane
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2964" type="surname" value="Lane"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2964" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2964" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                  ;" and that he, the said Richard Harper Green, afterwards, to wit, on the same day, at the same parish, feloniously did utter and publish as true, the said false, forged, and counterfeited acceptance of the said bill of exchange, with intent to defraud 
                     
                        <persName id="t18290409-321-victim2966" type="victimName">
                           Richard 
                           Finch
                        <interp inst="t18290409-321-victim2966" type="surname" value="Finch"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-321-victim2966" type="given" value="Richard"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18290409-321-victim2966" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-321-off1809 t18290409-321-victim2966"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , he, the said Richard Harper Green, at the time when he so uttered and published as true the said false, forget, and counterfeited acceptance, well knew the same to be false, forged. and counterfeited
            </rs>; against the Statute, &amp; c.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2967">
                  RICHARD 
                  FINCH
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2967" type="surname" value="FINCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2967" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2967" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18290409-321-viclabel1810" type="occupation">fender-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-321-victim2966 t18290409-321-viclabel1810"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18290409-321-crimeloc1811">Dudley, in Worcestershire</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-321-crimeloc1811" type="placeName" value="Dudley, in Worcestershire"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-321-crimeloc1811" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-321-off1809 t18290409-321-crimeloc1811"></join> - the prisoner sent me orders down into the country for goods. On the 17th of July he said he owed me 38l. 15s. 6d; he said he would give me this bill for 23l. 14s., and he would pay me the rest - he gave me the bill, and I took it with me into the country; he agreed to pay me the 15l. 1s. 6d., but he did not - at the time he gave me this bill I was at Mr. Stevens', the Rose and Crown public-house, in Little Britain; this is the bill - my son endorsed the bill in my presence; I paid it away, and it came back to me in the country.(The bill was here read as in the indictment.)</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. This bill became due on the 26th of September last? A. Yes; I had it returned to me unpaid - I staid about a fortnight, and then came to town - I went to Bull Head-court, and inquired about Mr. Lane; they said no such person lived there - I saw the prisoner afterwards, and he said he would give me another bill; I said it would be of no use - he did give me a bill for 18l.; this is it - it is drawn upon the prisoner; his brother was with him - (bill read)</p>
               <p>£18: 0: 0 Dudley, October 28, 1828, Two months after date pay to my order, Eighteen Pounds, value received, for RICHARD FINCH.</p>
               <p>To R.H.Green, No. 11, Harper-street, New Kent-road. Accepted, R.H.GREEN.</p>
               <p>Q. Did not his brother promise to see this hill paid? A. Yes - I cannot say when I made this charge against the prisoner; it was about five or six weeks ago, since he was taken up - it was long after the second bill became due; I had been stopping at his house several times in the interval, and this last time I lived and slept there for nine or ten nights - I think not more; that was after the second bill was returned - he was taken on another bill before I gave charge of him; I have seen John Green since the prisoner was charged with this bill, but he had nothing to do with it; I had one bill before on Mr. Lane, which the prisoner sent down into the country - I paid it away, and it was paid; I sold 
               <persName id="t18290409-321-person2968">
                  John 
                  Green
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2968" type="surname" value="Green"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2968" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2968" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             some fenders, and I took a bill of him, drawn on Nicholson, for them.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Was there another bill, which became due in February? A. Yes; I was in the country when it became due - I saw John Green last about five weeks ago; I have since been there, and he is removed.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2969">
                  THOMAS 
                  BROOKS
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2969" type="surname" value="BROOKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2969" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2969" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a housekeeper, and live at No. 4, Bull's Head-court, Snow-hill. I have kept the house these three years; no person named Lane has lodged there during that time - I let two rooms, but to no person of that name.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2970">
                  JAMES 
                  JOHNSON
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2970" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2970" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2970" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at the same house. I know no such name as Lane there; I know the prisoner, and he knew perfectly well where I lived; I have done little jobs for him now and then, when he has asked me, for the last two years - he has very often been to the house.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Was he enquiring after a person of the name of Lane? A. No; he was at the house about a week before he was taken, but I had no conversation with him on that occasion - I am not master of the house.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Was he every there in the course of 1828? A. Yes, my Lord, I am certain of that; he has been there to send me on errands on such a thing as that - he lived in the New Kent-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182904090150"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2971">
                  JOHN 
                  SWAIN
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2971" type="surname" value="SWAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2971" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2971" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went to Bull's Headcourt, but could find no such person as Lane.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2972">
                  RICHARD 
                  FINCH
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2972" type="surname" value="FINCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2972" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2972" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took another bill on Lane from the prisoner - I paid that away, and have not seen it since.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. This business was a transaction of my brother's, John Green; it was he that brought orders to me, and requested me to send the goods, saying Mr. Lane was a responsible person, and the bill would be paid; I had sent one lot of goods, for which he gave me a bill; that was paid; in consequence of that he came to me for other goods, and I had them sent - he gave me the bill which is now in question; it was entirely his transaction, and I depended on him: I never saw Lane myself, nor knew whether any such person lived there or not - he took the goods from me, and brought the bill to me accepted.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2973">
                  BARNARD 
                  BOYLE
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2973" type="surname" value="BOYLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2973" type="given" value="BARNARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2973" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to a notary. I presented this bill for 15l. 6s. on James Lane, at No. 4, Bull's Head-court, Snow-hill; I do not recollect who gave the answer, but it was, "Pay to-morrow," and the money was paid the next day.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-321-person2974">
                  RICHARD 
                  FINCH
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2974" type="surname" value="FINCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2974" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2974" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. When he gave me the bill, it had the acceptance of James Lane on it; the reason the other bill was for only 18l. was, he asked me if I would have an 18l. bill, I said, Yes, as I wanted it to pay my brassman.</p>
               <p>JURY to 
               <persName id="t18290409-321-person2975">
                  JAMES 
                  JOHNSON
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2975" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2975" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2975" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. Have you any remembrance of his giving you any orders to pay a bill that might be presented to your house? A. No, he never mentioned such a thing - I gave an answer to this bill, that Mr. Green was not there; I did not say when it would be paid - the prisoner asked me if there was a bill presented, and I said, Yes, and gave him the memorandum, and he said,"Tell them I will call to-morrow."</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did 
               <persName id="t18290409-321-person2976">
                  John 
                  Green
               <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2976" type="surname" value="Green"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2976" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-person2976" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             ever give you any orders? A. No.</p>
               <p>MR. BODKIN. Q. This conversation took place after the bill had been brought? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. Had you any previous notice that a bill would be brought? A. No; he came and asked me if there had not been a bill brought - I am quite sure there has not been a person of the name of Lane lodging there these four years, since I have been in the house; I was in the habit of taking him letters, and several bills came from the bankers, and I gave answer he was not there, or something of that kind.</p>
               <p>GUILTY - <rs id="t18290409-321-punish1812" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-punish1812" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-321-defend2962 t18290409-321-punish1812"></join>
               DEATH
            </rs>. Aged 47.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290409-321-verdict1813" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-verdict1813" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-321-verdict1813" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
               Recommended to mercy; the Jury believing he intended to pay the bill; and was greatly influenced by his brother
            </rs>.</p>
